  "prompt": "Are grapes bad for any breeds of dogs?",
  "response": "Grapes, as well as raisins, are **toxic to all breeds of dogs**, regardless of their size, age, or breed. Even small amounts can cause severe health issues, including acute kidney failure. The exact substance in grapes that causes toxicity is still unknown, but the effects can be life-threatening.\n\n### Symptoms of Grape or Raisin Toxicity in Dogs:\n- Vomiting\n- Diarrhea\n- Lethargy\n- Loss of appetite\n- Abdominal pain\n- Decreased urination\n- Weakness\n- Tremors\n\n### What to Do if Your Dog Eats Grapes or Raisins:\n1. **Contact your veterinarian or an emergency animal clinic immediately.**\n2. Do not induce vomiting unless instructed by a professional.\n3. Provide details about the amount and type (grapes, raisins, etc.) ingested.\n4. Follow your vet\u2019s instructions for treatment, which may include inducing vomiting, administering activated charcoal, or providing IV fluids.\n\n### Prevention:\n- Keep grapes, raisins, and foods containing them (e.g., trail mix, baked goods) out of your dog\u2019s reach.\n- Educate family members and visitors about the dangers of feeding grapes to dogs.\n\nIf you suspect your dog has ingested grapes or raisins, act quickly\u2014early intervention is critical to prevent serious complications.",
